chh.math.sets

Class Tuple

  • java.lang.Object
    • chh.math.sets.Set
      • chh.math.sets.Pair
        • chh.math.sets.Tuple

  • public class Tuple
extends Pair
    A Tuple (an ordered n-tuple) is the generalized concept of an ordered pair. An ordered n-tuple is written ⟨a,b,c,…⟩, where a, b, and c are the components. The number of components is n.

    An ordered n-tuple is a set that encodes the order of its components (which is only non-trivial for n > 1). For example, (new Tuple(a,b)).equals(new Tuple(b,a))==false (unless a.equals(b)), while (new Pair(a,b)).equals(new Pair(b,a))==true.



    new Tuple(a,b,c,d,...,y,z) is defined recursively by super(new Tuple(a,b,c,d,...,y), z), where the basis new Tuple() is defined by super(new EmptySet()).

    • Constructor Detail

      • Tuple

        public Tuple()
        Constructs a new Tuple object with no components (an ordered 0-tuple). An ordered 0-tuple ⟨⟩ is (a set) equal to the Singleton {{}}. Note that this is not equal to the EmptySet {}. The union of ⟨⟩ is the set that contains elements of {} (that is, the union of ⟨⟩ is empty).

      • Tuple

        public Tuple(Set a)
        Constructs a new Tuple object with one component (an ordered 1-tuple). The ordered 1-tuple ⟨a⟩ is defined by the pair {⟨⟩, a}, which is equal to {{{}},a}. Note that this is not equal to the Singleton {a}. The union of ⟨a⟩ is the set that contains the set {}, and elements of a.
        Parameters:
        a - the only component

      • Tuple

        public Tuple(Set a,
     Set b)
        Constructs a new Tuple object with two components (an ordered 2-tuple). The ordered 2-tuple ⟨a,b⟩ is defined by the pair {⟨a⟩,b}, which is equal to {{{{}},a},b}. Note that this is not equal to the OrderedPairAlternate (a,b). The union of ⟨a,b⟩ is the set that contains the tuple ⟨⟩, the set a, and elements of b.
        Parameters:
        a - the x-component (the abscissa)
        b - the y-component (the ordinate)

Note that this is not equal to the OrderedTriple (a,b,c). The union of ⟨a,b,c⟩ is the set that contains the tuple ⟨a⟩, the set b, and elements of c.
